{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930071001/0539.xml":{"full_text":"Cheerful Mood of Wall Street Not Sign of Bullishness, Spectator Warns\nTraders\u00dfearishDespite\nHigher Price Trend\nHeavy Odd Lot Buying Giving Stocks Re\nsistance Cushion and Strengthening\nPosition; Meehan Returning\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nWall Street is more cheerful today. The market\u2019s strength\nyesterday following Tuesday\u2019s rally is responsible, but this is\nnot to be taken as a sign of returning bullishness.\nThe majority in the street will lean to bearishness, some\nrampantly so for the immediate pull, while the others merely\ncontent themselves with saying that they do not think prices\nwill go much lower. Washington and banking circles are re\nported less pessimistic than Wall Street, declaring that brokers\nare getting a warped view of security values from being too\nclose to the picture.\nThe market is very thin both ways. There is no reaching\nfor stocks on rallies. While specialists\u2019 books, I am told, are not\nheavily loaded with orders on the way down. Yet heavy odd\nlot buying for cash and scale down investment purchasing is\nstill going on, giving stocks a resistance cushion and strengthen\ning their position.\nThe best advice at present is to stay on the sidelines. A\nnimble trader may be able to scalp a profit either way, but a\nfew points look large today and in most cases are not worth\nthe risk.\nPools\nThere was more talk of pools\nbeing reformed yesterday than\nthere has been for some time.\nThis is in addition to the huge\nbull pool, led by Durant- and Mee\nhan. Wall Street has been hear\ning about to start the market up\nward. Stocks linked to the new\nblocs are Vanadium and General\nMotors, the latter in connection\nwith the report that the Wilming\nton crowd has begun to buy\nstocks.\nMeehan is due back from abroad\nSaturday. Activity in radio yes\nterday. was believed to be in the\nnature of a \u201cpre welcome home\u201d\ndemonstration. Meehan may\nstart some \u201cfireworks\u201d on his re\nturn trip but. as some one aptly\nput it, no one knows whether he\nis bullish or bearish.\nThe Oils\nAction of the big oil companies,\nled by Standard Oil of New Jer\nsey, in cutting gasoline runs to\nreduce huge stocks on hand, is a\nhopeful sign that the oils may\nyet \u201cget out of the woods.\u201d Crude\noil production seems well in hand.\nMany brokers, however, are still\nskeptical. One told me that he\ndidn\u2019t like the oil situation at\nall, yet added that he had been\ntold he was crazy and that the\npowers that be at 26 Broadway\n(Standard Oil) were confident\nthat a turn for the better had\ncome. The situation will be im\nproved when and if the rumored\nmergers take place. Supply will\nthus be concentrated and will be\nmore susceptible to curtailment.\nOil well supply is latest low\npriced stock to enter the \u2018mystery\u2019\nstage. It was up 4% points to\n20% yesterday, and has more\nthan doubled in price in the last\nfew weeks. It looks much like\nstrong-arm pool work, though\n5 earnings in the second quarter\nare said to have shown a sharp\nrise. Yet the company showed a\ndeficit of over $7 a share last\nyear and a small loss the year\nbefore.\nBrokers Loans\nBrokers loans should be lower\ntoday, but the drop if any will\nprobably be smaller. Several\nbrokers, report declines in their\nloan totals, but of no great dimen\nsions. It doesn\u2019t matter either\nway. Loans at present are at\ntheir low for a long time. Expir\ning rights this past week totalled\nCOBLISTFGS\nAPPROVED\nBoard of Governors of the Curb\nExchange at their weekly meet\ning approved the admittance to\nunlisted trading privileges of the\nfollowing securities:\nAustin Motor Co., Ltd., Guar\nanty Trust Co. American deposi\ntary receipts for ordinary regis\ntered shares, par 5 shillings:\nHamburg Electric Co.. Hamburg\nische Elect ricitaets Werke-Guar\nanty Trust Co. American deposi\ntary receipts for common bearer\nshares: Gelsenkirchen Mining Co.,\nGelsenkirchner Bergwerks Aktien\ngesellschaft-Guaranty Trust Co.\nAmerican depositary receipts for\ncommon bearer shares: American\nForeign Power Co., part paid\nallotment certificates evidencing\npayment of first, second, third,\nfourth and fifth instalments to\ntaling 80 per cent of subscription\nprice for units consisting of sec\nond preferred stock and option\nwarrants.\nThe following security has been\nremoved from unlisted trading\nprivilege?:\nAmerican Foreign Power Co.,\npart paid allotment certifications\nevidencing payment of first, sec\nond, third and fourth instalments\nof subscription price for units.\nSave time in locating needed eervleea\nfcy turnin* to the Buelneee Service Di\nlatory of today* Claulfied Ad*.\nWASHINGTON TIHESSFIIiANCIM. NEWS\nabout $50,000,000 and this may\naffect the result.\nI hear that the first pool in\nWarner Brothers that carried to\nthe stock above 80 made a royal\n\u2018killing.\u2019 The stock was liquidated\nall the way up, I am told, and\nprice the pool averaged 74 for its\nholdings which were said to have\nbeen acquired at less than 50.\nGroup Movements\nOne interesting fact pointed\nout to me by the statistician for\nI a large brokerage house was that\nI only two groups, the tobaccos\nand the amusements, still show\ngains -for the year. The food\ngroup reveals the most stability.\nAll the rest broke into new low\nground. The chemical and avia\ntion groups, he declares, will\nshow the biggest gain in the\nnext five years.\nA scale by interests who are\nconvinced that the $2 dividend\nis assured. Earnings, it is re\nported, are being affected by\noperation economies as well as\nincreasing export demand. The\ncompany has shown steadily ris\ning profits in the last decade and\nits new plant for the production\nof high-test hypochorite is near\ning completion.\nThe Motors\nThere is a golden harvest in\nthe motors provided there is any\nassurance that the current divi\ndend rates are safe. Nash went\non a $4 basis yesterday, but the\nstock is still selling around 34.\nyielding about 12 per cent, and\nthis high rate of return is typi\ncal of many in the group. Even\nGeneral Motors yields better than\n7 per cent, and I am told that\nits earnings for the second quar\nter will be better than $1.25 a\nshare, bringing first halt net\nabove $2 on the stock. Vacation\nshut downs will cut sharply into\nprofits for the third quarter, yet\nmotor companies are well forti\nfied with cash and have done a\nsplenid job so far this year in\nkeeping production in line with\nsales.\nA brokerage house that has\ntaken a conservatively bullish\nposition in the market tells me\nthat its loan ratio is down to a\nfigure that has always meant the\nbeginning of an advance in the\npast. Another points out that\nthe present brokers\u2019 loans total\nis less than the combined capi\ntalization of General Motors and\nAmerican Telephone. Yet no\nbroad upward movement is seen\nunless Steel crosses 162, Consoli\ndated Gas 110, and telephone 211.\nGAR LOADINGS\nGAIN IN WEEK\nLoading of revenue freight for\nthe week ended June 28 totaled\n936.848 cars the American Railway\nAssociation announced today. This\nwas an increase of 15,989 cars\nabove the preceding week but a\nreduction of 159,721 cars under\nthe same week in 1929.\nMiscellaneous freight loading\nfor the week totaled 371,999 cars,\n68,442 cars under the same week\nin 1929. Loading of merchandise\nless than carload lot freight\namounted to 239,544 cars, a de\ncrease of 21,161 cars below the\ncorresponding week last year.\nCoal loading amounted to 137,-\n521 cars, a decrease of 24,534 cars\nbelow the same week in 1929. For\nest products loading amounted to\n47,947 cars, 21,551 cars under the\nsame week in 1929.\nOr 3 loading amounted to 61,034\ncars, a decrease of 15,623 carfc be\nlow the same week in 1929. Coke\nloading amounted to 9,391 cars, a\ndecrease of 2,886 cars below the\ncorresponding week last year.\nFRAT HAS OUTING\nA moonlight excursion will be\nheld by Alpha Sigma Damda fra\nternity on the Wilson Line\nsteamer City of Washington to\nmorrow night. The boat will\nleave the foot of Seventh Street\nat o\u2019clock.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nAt Parley\n'it I\nin\nml\n\u2014Tinies Sluff Photo\nTHOMAS E. JARRELL\nPRESIDENT OF the Wash\nington Savings Bank and well\nknown local realtor, who is at\ntending the convention of the\nNational Association of Real\nEstate Boards in Toronto,\nCanada.\n81HEWS\nshow pun\nBy LESLIE GOULD.\nSavings deposits in Manhat\ntan\u2019s 27 savings banks this year\nhave established a high record\nfor all time.\nMoney on deposit in Wall\nStreet\u2019s billion dollar commrecial\nbanks is millions ahead of a year\nago. The totals in most coses are\nnew records.\nThis certainly is no indicator\nof a hard-up people.\nThe buying power is there. AU\nthat is needed is something to\nawaken it. When it is, and peo\nple start replacing the clothing\nand shoes and other things they\nhave been wearing out, but hold\ning off buying for the last six\nmonths there wiH be a business\nrevival.\nHow soon this will come is any\nbody's guess, but one thing is cer\ntain, people cannot go on for\never wearing the same suit oi\nclothes or dress or pair of shoes\nThey must wear out.\nI Savings bank deposits in Man\nhattan on July 1 totaled $2,196,-\n426,618. This is a gain of $115,-\n881,680 since the first of the year,\nwhen total deposits were $2,080,-\n544,938. Deposits a year ago were\n$2,112,063,880, with the gain for\nyear\u2014July 1 to July 1\u2014574,362,-\n738.\nThe stock market crash last\nfall brought the drop in savings\nthe last half of the year, but since\nthen the New York savings ac\ncount depositor has more than\nmade up his withdrawals made\nin response to brokers\u2019 margin\ncalls.\nThe small speculator\u2014the man\nwith the savings account\u2014was\nnot in the market to any great\nextent in the 1921-22 break. This\nis shown by the steady rise in\nsavings through 1921 and 1922.\nSavings accounts on January 1,\n1920 totaled $1,128,493,878; on\nJanuary 1, 1921, 1,243,754,482; on\nJanuary 1, 1922, $1,333,866,352,\nand on January 1, 1923, $1,429,-\n012,543.\nThe significant thing in the\npresent case is the quick recovery\nby the savings accounts. In the\nlast half of last year they were\nseriously impaired by the stock\nmarket break, but now the total\nis far in excess of the previous\nrecord figures of a year ago.\nThis shows a sane state of mind\non the part of the \u201clittle fellow.\u201d\nHe has paid up for the most part\nhis stock market losses and has\nbeen able to put some additional\nmoney away.\nMachinery Buying\nAt Year's Low Point\nDemand in the Nation\u2019s ma\nchinery and machine-tool markets\nis almost negligible, with the\nusual summer slackness, a short\nweek occasioned by Independence\nDay, and general business quiet\nude all contributing to the small\nest week in the current year,\nAmerican Machinist, reports.\nInquiries are slow and the used\ntool market shares the quiet of\nthat for new tools. Prices, how\never, are being maintained and\ndeliveries are better than they\nhave been for many months.\nNew York reporst no additional\nlists and little business during the\nweek. New England sales of road\nbuilding and construction ma\nchinery are good, but most other\nlines are ver; slow.\nStraus Nat. Bank\nAnd Trust Co. Grows\nThe Straus National Bank and\nTrust Company of Chicago has\njust cele /rated its second birthday\nanniversary. According to a\nstatement made by the bank, de\nposits vhich on the opening day\nwere $2,085,000 in the two years\nhave grown to $15,881,584. Dur\ning the past year savings accounts\nhave increased 75 per cent it was\nreported. The bank personnel has\nincreased from 19 to 79.\nI.C.C. Action in Giving\nVan Sweringen Lease\nRight Seen Significant\nAction of the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission in giving the\nVan Sweringen-controlled Missouri\nPacific Railroad tentative au\nthority to lease 23 Southwestern\nlines, and outlining to it the\nsteps in formulating a giant sys\ntem patterned after the commis\nsion\u2019s general consolidation plan,\nwas regarded today as highly sig\nnificant.\nFailure of Congress to pass the\nresolution of Senator Couzens\n(RJ, of Michigan, aimed to post\npone any action by the commis\nsion looking to the consolidation\nof railroads until there had been\nfurther inquiry into the activities\nof holding companies, made the\ncommission\u2019s action in the Mis\nsouri Pacific case significant be\ncause the decision was reached\non June 2 and was not announced\nuntil July, after Congress had\nadjourned.\nObservers see in the commis\nsion\u2019s action an opportunity for\nthe Van Sweringen brothers, of\nCleveland, to get in on the\nground floor in setting up a sys\ntem that would cover a large\npart of the country and would\nconform to the commission\u2019s gen\neral plan for the No. 18 system,\nwhich would be known as the\nMissouri Pacific system.\n\u25a0ffl\nPACT URGED\nThe Cuban sugar situation was\ndiscussed today at a luncheon\ngiven at the Recess Club by\nThomas L. Chadbourne, attorney\nof the Matanzas Sugar Company\nattended by representatives of the\nAmerican sugar industry in Cuba\nand by Cuban sugar interests. A\ncommittee was named to study\nthe proposal of the Java and Eu\nropean producers for an interna\ntional agreement to regulate sugar\nproduction during the next five\nyears. Representatives of the en\ntire Cuban sugar industry are un\nderstood to be represented on the\ncommittee.\nAnother committee was ap\npointed to obtain a release of\nsugars pledged to bapks operating\nin Cuba so that members of the\nSanta Clara Producers Associa\ntion, now in New York, can work\nwith American members of the\ncommittee on a proposal pre\nsented by the Soviet government.\nThis proposal Is to buy Cuban\nsugar in lots of 100,000 tons\nmonthly up to December this\nyear, paying part in cash and\nremainder in notes guaranteed by\nRussion State Bank.\nBond Opinions Are\nListed by N. Y. Firm\nConvertible bonds, in the pres\nent market situation, provide the\ninvestor with an opportunity to\nprofit by an advance in the stock\nmarket without taking the major\nrisk involved in stock commit\nments, in the opinion of New\nburger, Henderson and Loeb,\nmembers of the New York Stock\nExchange.\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs Jn\nSALES\nPotomac Electric cons 5s $3,000\n@lO2.\nWashington Gas 5s SLOOO@\n103 2\nCapital Traction Company 2@\n58%, 10@60.\n.Washington Railway Electric\npfd., 5@98 1 8 9@98.\nUnion Trust Company, 10\n250.\nLanston Monotype, 10@115, 10\n@lls, 10@115, 10@115.\nMerchants Transfer Storage\npfd., 10@96, 10@96.\nMerganthaler Linotype 5@96V 2\nPeoples Drug Stores pfd., 3@\n104.\nAFTER CALL.\nNorfolk Washington Steam\nboat rts wi 56@16, I@l6.\nCapital Traction Company 10\n60, 5@60 1 4 10@60\u2018/4. 10@60y 2\nl@6o*/2, 10@61.\nPublic Utility Honda t Bid I Ask.\nAmer Tel Telga 414 s \u201933.. 1101 1......\nAmer Tel Telga 4**s \u201939.1160 1....\nAm Tel Tel Ctl Tr 55....1105%)\nAnacostia Pot HR 5s I 32 I\nAna Pot Guar 5s I 94\nc p Tel of Va 6s 1102141\nCap Traction R R 5s i 91141 94\nCity ft. Suburban 6s I 60 i 83\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 5s 1101141104\nPotomac Elec Cons 5s 102 I\nPotomac Elec 6s 101 1.....\nWash Alex 4 Mt V Ctf 6\nWash Balto An 5s 65 I\nWashington Gas 5s ....1103 10414\nWash Gas 6s series A 1102 110314\nWash Gas 6s series B 1105 1105\nWash By A Blec 45........1 86 1 Bf\u00bb4\n\u25a0Miscellaneous Bonds I I\nBarber Ross Inc 6145. ...I 89 90\nChevy Chase Club 5145....i100\nD C Paper Mfg 6s 50 70\nW M Cold Storage 5s 195\nWash Cons Ttile 6s I 87 |IOO\nPublic Utility Stocks t_ I\n\u2022d Amer Tel ft Te! 1206%!.....\nCapitol Traction Co I 60 I 61\nWash Gas Lt Co 1115 |132\n<IN ft W Steamboat 1215 1255\nN ft W Steamboat Rte w 1.1 15 I 16*\u00bb\nPot Elec Pow 6s pfd 111014 111 2\nPot Eleo Pwr l%s pfd 11071,110814\nWash Ry ft Ei 1550 I\nTha National Daily\nThe Van Sweringens have\nother plans in contemplation\napart from those connected with\nthe Missouri Pacific, and now\nthat they have been given a cue\nby the commission, it is ex\npected they bring these into the\nopen \u201cwhile the going is good.\u201d\nIf they made their application\nconform to the ideas of the com\nmission it appears they will con\nsummate the first real railroad\nconsolidation plan in recent\nyears. The great Northern-\nNorthern Pacific merger, which\nhas been conditionally approved\nby the commission, has been\ntemporarily held up, and may\nreach the courts. Many other\nmerger propositions have also\nstruck snags because they did\nnot conform with policies es\ntablished by the commission.\nThe Van Sweringens have\nmade it plain they do not con\ntemplate setting up a great\ntranscontinental system under\none management. Their lines.\nEast and West of the Mississippi,\nwill be separate and integral sys\ntems. In the East, the Chesa\npeake and Ohio will be the main\nstem, while beyond the Missis\nsippi, the Missouri Pacific will be\ntheir dominant road, with all its\nseeded lines.\nCIHLATIONf\nMONEY OFF\nThere was $225,000,000 less\nmoney in circulation on June 30\nthan a year ago, the Treasury an\nnounced today.\nThe total volume of money in\ncirculation was $4,521,832,000, or\n$37.30 per capital, compared to\n$39.62 per capita June 30, 1929.\nThe total stock of money June\n30 was $8,305,769,000. a reduction\nof $233,000,000 during the year.\nThe Treasury held $4,021,287,000,\nan increase of $232,000,000 during\nthe year. The figures were based\non an estimated population of\n121,213,000, although the Census\nBureau fixes the population at a\nsomewhat higher figure.\nThe large reduction in circula\ntion as compared to a year ago\nis due to the recession in busi\nness, resulting in a lack of de\nmand for currency. Last June the\ncountry was in the midst of an\nunprecedented wave of prosperity\nand rapidly mounting stock prices,\nwhich created an abnormal de\nmand for currency and drove in\nterest rates to record levels.\nToday money is cheap.\nInterpreter Needed\nIn Mercantile Suit\nA case in which an interpreter\nhad to be called to translate\ntestimony of the defendant was\nsettled in Municipal Court by\nJudge Robert E. Mattingly when\nJoseph Futrovsky, wholesale meat\ndealer, was awarded judgment\nagainst Israel Mensh for S6OO.\nFutrovsky had* brought suit\nagainst Mensh on an open ac\ncount.\nBid Ask\nWash Ry El pfd I 9* 99\nWash Balto An com i a\nWash Balto An pfd..... .1 6\nNational Bank Stocks I I\nCapital 250 1250\nColumbia 400 I\nCommercial (stamped) 227'41240\nDistrict 213 1250\nFederal-American 275 1300\nLiberty 200 |220\nLincoln 400 1435\nMetropolitan 330 |365\nRiggs 475 1505\nSecond t............ 175 |2lO\nWashington 245 |250\nTrust Company Stocks I I\n\u2022Amer Sec Tr Co.. |375 |415\nContinental Trust 1120 |l4O\nMerch Bank Trust 1125 |l4O\nNational Sav Trust.... |540 1585\n\u2022Union Trust |249 |275\nWash Loan rpr |460 1510\nSavings Bank Stocks I\nBank of Bethesda I 59 65\nCom! Savings |330\nEast Washington 20 35\nPotomac Sav Bank 15 I 75\nSec Sav Coml Bank (271 |SOO\nSeventh Street |3lO\nUnited States |530 I\nWashington Mechanics ....I 50 I\nFire Insurance Stocks i I\nAmerican |3on\nCorcoran 2OO\nr tremens 36'41 40\nNational Union 23 I 26\nTitle insurance Stocks I I\nColumbia Bii| jo\nE tatl3 J 155 1175\nritle Inv Co Md com... J 20 I 30\nMiacellaneous Stocks I I\nBarber Ross Inc c0m....1 15 I IS\nChevy Chase Dairy pfd ...403 1109\nCol Sand Grav pfd 89 I 94\nD C Paper Mfg pfd... 10 1.....\nDiet Natl Sec pfd.... 1 I 70 I 85\nEnter Bromo Selz A I 30 I 33\n\u2022Federal Storage pfd 1110 1125\nFed-Amer Co com 30 I 33\nFed-Amer Co nfd I 99 HOO\nLanston Monotype |114%|114U\n-'V* r Ter Stge com 1103 H >lO6\nMer Tr A Stge pfd.v 96 I 98\nMergenthaler Lino 95\u20194 97\nNatl Mtge A Inv pfd i 4\u201941 514\nPennies Drug S nfd 1102'51106\nReal Est M A G pfd I 6% I 7\nSecurity Storage 1113 .1117\nTer Ref A Wh Corp I 47 I 53\nThe Carpel Corp I 22 I 24\nW Meeh Mtae com I 9 <4! 10\nWash Med Bldg Corn i 93 I\nWoodward A Lothrop pfd..11\u00ab5 Illi\n*Ex.divtdend.\nTHURSDAY, JULY 10, 1930\nAMERICAN FEE.\nGROSS IIP, BUT\nNET DROPS\nPeoples Light and Power Re*\nports Balance for Dividends\nTo Equal $4.18 Per Share\nAlthough gross income of the\nAmerican Telephone and Tele\ngraph Company for May was\nhigher, net for the month fell off\n$460,154 to $2,880,725 against\n$3,340,879 in May, 1928. Gross in\ncome for May was $9,821,523, com\npared With $9,210,357 in May, 1929.\nNet operating income for the five\nmonths ended May 30, amounted\nto $15,177,139. against $17,418,629\nin the same 1929 period. Gross in\ncome for the period totaled S4B,\n685,246, against $45,868,302 in the\ncorresponding 1929 period,\nPeople\u2019s Light\nPeople\u2019s Light and Power Com\npany. subsidiary of the Tri-Utili\nties Corporation, reports for the\nyear ended May 31 a balance avail\nable for dividends on the common\nstock of $4.13 a share on the aver\nage number of class A common\nshares outstanding during the pe\nriod.\nOhio Water Service\nOhio Water Service Company re\nports for the year ended May 31\ngross income after general expen\nses and taxes of $394,056, com\npared with $370,889 in the preced\ning year.\nCanada Power\nCanada Northern Power Com\npany reports net income for the\nfive months ended May 31 of\n$923,202. against $930,630 in the\nsame 1929 period.\nOil Stocks Dividend\nIs Distributed\nP. W. Brooks Co., sponsors,\nannounce that a semi-annual cash\ndistribution on Associated Stand\nard Oil stocks shares, coupon No.\n2. will be paid on July 15. 1980,\nat the rate of approximately 90\ncents per share by the Empire\nTrust Company of New York City,\ntrustee.\nBreeding by the Millions Hatched in Unspeakable Filth\nDrenched with Dreadful, Disease-Carrying Bacteria\nTHE\nFEARFUL\nFLY\n<tOACH-,\nJOrT* rLIA\nMO BU\u00ab\nFLY-TOXI\nKILLS THEM. ALL\nAvoid the venom of the mosquito\u2019s piercing dagger. He injects\ndisease germs directly into the blood stream. Prevent infection\nfrom the fly\u2019s putrescent ooze. He spreads thirty different diseases.\nKill the destructive moth \u2014the defiling cockroach. Enjoy healthful r mI\ncleanliness and security always. Keep FLY-TOX handy. Fatal to\nthe Fearful Seven. Refuse substitutes \u2014there is only one FLY\nTOX. Every bottle guaranteed.\nKnis\nFLY-TOX was developed at Mellon Institute of\nIndustrial Research by Rex Research Fellowship.\nABSOLUTELY HARMLESS TO PEOPLE AND ANIMALS\nBack Home I\njf b\n\u25a0HI 7.\nI K I\n9 I\na\n\u25a0k\niRk HiLIL\n\u2014Time* Staff Photo\nGEORGE A. GARRETT\nRESIDENT PARTNER of F. B.\nKeech and Co., New York in\nvestment bankers, who returned\nyesterday from a short vacation\nwhich he spent at his summer\nhome in Newport, R. I.\nPhillips Co. Buys\nFiftieth Gas Plant\nPhillips Petroleum Company an\nnounce the purchase, for a con\nsideration of $325,000, of the com\nplete natural gasoline plant of the\nDixon-Creek Oil Company, near\nBorger, Texas, thus adding 12,000\ngallons to the Phillips production\nand furnishing an added outlet\nfor residue gas sales of eight to\nten million cubic feet daily.\nThis purchase carries with it\nnatural gas contracts covering\nsome 2,500 acres on which there\nis considerable undrilled proven\npotential. This plant is Phillips\u2019\nfiftieth natural gasoline plant and\nbecomes a part of its major sys\ntem, through which large scale\noperations are carried on with\nconsequent production economies,\nand further fortifies the Phillips\nposition in a territory in which\nthey are already predominant.\nBACKLOGS AID\nSTEEL, OUTPUT\nSTEPPED DP\nTrade Journal Says Operators\nWill Keep Production Near\nPresent Rate Until Change\nBacklogs in pipe steel and tin\nplate, plus good commitments in\nreinforcing bars and a large vol\nume of structural steel tonnage,\nare counted on to hold steel pro\nduction within a few points of the\npresent rate of mill operations un\ntil general improvement In de\nmand sets in, Iron Age said to\nday in its trade review.\nIron and steel demand, the re\nview continues, has not recovered\nthe ground lost during the holi\nday interruption and it will taae\na week or two before the volume\ncf current business can be gauged.\nMany consuming plants are still\nshut down for inventory, and sus\npensions among automobile arid\nautomotive parts markers will last\ntwo weeks or longer. The Ford\nMotor Company will stop opera\ntions from July 11 to 28 and has\ncut off all shipments of steel.\nRailroad Car builders are reaching\nthe end of their orders, three\nshops in the Chicago district hav\ning shut down, with others run\nning at 25 to 40 per cent of capac\nity. Operations of farm equip\nment plants have reached the\nlowest point of the year. Western\nrail mills are now on a 25 per\ncent basis and have little remain\ning tonnage to roll.\nSteel ingot production, after\nthe sharp reduction in operations\nfollowing last Thursday, now\naverages 56 per cent of capacity,\ncompared with 60 per cent at the\nbeginning of last week. Recovery\nin mill operations has been most\nmarked in plants making line\npipe, 'which have been stepped up\nsharply to an 80 to 90 per cent\nrate. Tin plate output again\naverages 70 per cent, and plate\nproduction in the Chicago dis\ntrict has rebounded as a result\nof demands from the Milwaukee\nmaker of electrically-welded pipe.\nShipments are moving forward\nto the Wisconsin pipe shop at\nthe rate of 55,000 tons a month.\n21","height":"30329","width":"24077"}}
